Hmm, maybe I understand it wrongly. My current code is working properly with 0.25.
Once I try to Regenerate all things with 0.25 based on the same swagger I got these changes:


```  
// environment
        // Required: true
-       Environment EnvironmentName `json:"environment"`
+       Environment *EnvironmentName `json:"environment"`
```

Happens on all my Enum fields currently...


```
const (

	// EnvironmentNameDev captures enum value "dev"
	EnvironmentNameDev EnvironmentName = "dev"

	// EnvironmentNameTest captures enum value "test"
	EnvironmentNameTest EnvironmentName = "test"

	// EnvironmentNameQas captures enum value "qas"
	EnvironmentNameQas EnvironmentName = "qas"

	// EnvironmentNameProd captures enum value "prod"
	EnvironmentNameProd EnvironmentName = "prod"

	// EnvironmentNameMock captures enum value "mock"
	EnvironmentNameMock EnvironmentName = "mock"
)
```


so before I used to use: 

```
apimodel.EnvironmentName(c.EnvironmentName)
```

So the code is broken when I use 0.26 - what's the best practice here?

@fredbi

@iamtakingiteasy regarding your request, how about a help factory like this one?
I am sticking to the string case only, since that the only case now for which we generate `const`.

```go
// SodaBrand Some top level description
//
// swagger:model SodaBrand
type SodaBrand string

func NewSodaBrand(value SodaBrand) *SodaBrand {
	v := value
	return &v
}

const (

	// SodaBrandOTHERBRAND captures enum value "OTHER_BRAND"
	SodaBrandOTHERBRAND SodaBrand = "OTHER_BRAND"

	// SodaBrandPEPSI captures enum value "PEPSI"
	SodaBrandPEPSI SodaBrand = "PEPSI"

	// SodaBrandCOKE captures enum value "COKE"
	SodaBrandCOKE SodaBrand = "COKE"

	// SodaBrandCACTUSCOOLER captures enum value "CACTUS_COOLER"
	SodaBrandCACTUSCOOLER SodaBrand = "CACTUS_COOLER"

	// SodaBrandJOLT captures enum value "JOLT"
	SodaBrandJOLT SodaBrand = "JOLT"
)
```

or maybe more flexible:
```go

func NewSodaBrand(value ...SodaBrand) *SodaBrand {
	var v *SodaBrand
        for _, w := range value {
            *v = w
        }
	return v
}
```

@fredbi 

(EDIT: there was unedited version of my reply where I made a potentially dangerous suggestion to take pointer of argument itself. Sorry about possible confusion. Current version should be fine.)

> ```go
> func NewSodaBrand(value SodaBrand) *SodaBrand {
> 	v := value
> 	return &v
> }
> ```

This looks fine.

Regarding your follow-up:

> ```go
> func NewSodaBrand(value ...SodaBrand) *SodaBrand {
> 	var v *SodaBrand
>         for _, w := range value {
>             *v = w
>         }
> 	return v
> }
> ```

This should produce nil-pointer dereference and I don't see a point assigning same local variable over and over again from list of arguments.

Maybe you meant array/list/slice version of same function:

```go
func NewSodaBrandList(values ...SodaBrand) (arr []*SodaBrand) {
	// `make` to reduce number of possible reallocations from `append`
	arr = make([]*SodaBrand, len(values))

	for i := range values {
		// this shouldn't use &values[i], nor address of loop variable in 
		// second place of `for` directly to avoid referencing memory location that
		// would be overwritten on next function call or next loop iteration
		// instead, copy the value under new memory location
		c := values[i]
		arr[i] = &c
	}

	return
}
```

@iamtakingiteasy yeah you're right, returning a nil pointer is not a good idea.
The vararg version just came on top of my mind as I know of some other issue (#1393) for which the obvious solution
would be to generalize factory functions (i.e. `New{{ model }}`) for all generated models. This shouldn't conflict with a specific factory for enumerated types...
